We congratulate our Executive Director Kim M. Webb for being selected as the 2022 VUCA Honoree with Leadership Council For Nonprofits This award recognizes an early-career leader in the Greater Cincinnati nonprofit sector who is positively impacting their organization and the community through demonstrated Vision, Understanding, Clarity & Agility while operating in a Volatile, Uncertain, Complex & Ambiguous world. Kim is a tireless advocate for adults experiencing homelessness. She exhibits grace under pressure while managing & navigating challenging political situations, patiently persuading the community that a warm, safe bed is a right not a privilege. She has worked and struggled to lead the shelter to a state of the art building that improves the work environment for staff but is also a place where guests can not only rest, but find resources to help them move from homeless to housed. We congratulate all the honorees for their achievements. You can learn more about all honorees and how to register for the Securing the Future Conference by visiting https://www.leadershipcouncil.us/programs/securing-the-future-conference/:=:https://www.leadershipcouncil.us/programs/securing-the-future-conference/about-the-conference/

In a recent episode of the Collaborative Farmingpodcast, Tallahassee May explains the Growing Together program of The Nashville Food Project, which leases a few acres of inner city land for Bhutan and Burmese farmers, most of them elders, so they may grow produce both for their famalies and community, make a supplemental income, and have meaningful work. The amount of food the farmers in the Growing Together program produce on just a handful of acres within the city is incredible, and their work is helping the city to change the way it thinks about local food and land use. üëâüèΩ Being able to produce food locally matters. üëâüèΩ Being able to preserve and steward the last bits of urban green spaces left using ecologically-friendly practices matters. üëâüèΩ Being able to see agriculture happen from the school bus window or from the seat of a bicycle, and how that influences the youth's connection to land and food matters. üëâüèΩ Urban agriculture matters. #urbanfarming #urbanfarm #Blackfarmers #regenerativeagriculture #localfood

Click Link https://amzn.to/3IoGzKr:=:https://www.amazon.com/s?k=George+Altman+baseball&crid=313N69QYT1VLQ&sprefix=george+altman+baseball%2Caps%2C50 To Order Or Review George Altman: My Baseball Journey from the Negro Leagues to the Majors and Beyond HAPPY BIRTHDAY to George Altman. March 20, 1933 George Lee Altman was born in Goldsboro, NC. He was a former Major League Baseball outfielder and Nippon Professional Baseball outfielder. He batted left-handed and threw right-handed. Altman's first professional baseball experience was with the Kansas City Monarchs of the Negro Leagues; he played three months for the team in 1955. Altman played for the Chicago Cubs (from 1959 to 1962, and from 1965 to 1967), St. Louis Cardinals (1963), and New York Mets (1964). In a nine-season MLB career, Altman had a .269 batting average with 101 home runs and 403 RBIs, in 991 games played. He played professional baseball in Japan from 1968 through 1975, for the Lotte Orions and the Hanshin Tigers, where he had a .309 batting average with 205 home runs. Highlights from his NPB career included leading the Pacific League in hits (170), runs (84), and RBI (100) in 1968; and being named to the "Best Nine" Pacific League team in 1968, 1970, and 1971. He credited martial arts training for baseball success in Japan. He is an alumnus of Tennessee State University and currently resides in O'Fallon, Missouri. Shirley Chisholm (1924-2005) was the first Black Congresswoman and the first African American to run for President. Born in Brooklyn, she became involved in local Democratic party politics in the 1950s, leading to her election as state legislator despite facing discrimination for being female. A decade later, she made history through an upset election victory to become the first Black woman to sit in Congress. As a Congresswoman, she supported expansions of social services, fought for indigenous land rights, and helped found the Congressional Black Caucus among other achievements. She also opposed the Vietnam War and fiercely advocated for the Equal Rights Amendment. In 1972, she became the first African American to run for a major party‚Äôs nomination for President and the first woman to appear in a presidential debate. While her campaign was unsuccessful, she blazed a trail for future generations. In 1983, Chisholm retired from Congress to return to her original dreams of teaching, serving as a Professor at Mount Holyoke College and speaking at universities around the nation. In 1993, she was inducted into the National Women‚Äôs Hall of Fame and, in 2015, was posthumously awarded the Presidential Medal of Freedom. The inscription on her memorial at the Birchwood Mausoleum captures her legacy: ‚ÄúUnbought and Unbossed.‚Äù #BlackHistoryMonth2022 #UWNYC #LiveUnited

Sometimes, people are critical of ‚Äúgentle parenting,‚Äù (also known as respectful parenting or empowered parenting.) That criticism often stems from misconceptions. Some people believe that gentle parenting means never disciplining your children, never using a stern tone, or always letting kids get their way. This week on the podcast, we are joined by parenting coach, and author of the upcoming book Very Intentional Parenting @destini.ann to discuss what gentle parenting really does (and doesn‚Äôt) look like. See an excerpt from the podcast blog post below ‚§µÔ∏è Destini likes to say that she puts her foot down‚Äîshe just does it gently. Empowered parenting involves firm but gentle boundaries. It also includes acceptance and understanding when your children have big feelings in response to those boundaries. She pointed out that people often think empowered parents aren‚Äôt holding boundaries. But the very fact that children are displaying big feelings is evidence that they are. If gentle parents always gave in, their children would be happy all the time‚Äìnot openly expressing frustration, disappointment, or anger. But sometimes observers perceive that expression as disrespect. As she said, ‚ÄúIt‚Äôs almost as if they want us to punish our kids when they don‚Äôt like our discipline.‚Äù Sometimes adults expect more from their children than they do from adults. They demand that children control their emotions, but they yell at them. They give demands to children, ordering them to ‚Äúask nicely.‚Äù We often ask too much of children but don‚Äôt model desired behaviours for them. Head to happyasamother.co/blog:=:https://happyasamother.co/blog to read more or listen to Episode 126 with @destini.ann

#DidYouKnow For roughly 12 years the Massachusetts Anti-Slavery Society held rallies at Framingham's Harmony Grove. Many famous abolitionists spoke at these events including William Lloyd Garrison, Lucy Stone, Wendell Phillips, Sojourner Truth, Henry David Thoreau, etc. This broadside announces the 19th anniversary of the abolition of slavery in the British West Indies in 1853; still 10 years before President Lincoln's "The Emancipation Proclamation." #BlackHistoryMonth Image: West India Emancipation: Celebration at Framingham, Boston Public Library.

A man carried out seven assaults on women of Asian descent in just two hours on Sunday in Manhattan, police said. All of the attacks were spread across Midtown, Gramercy Park, NoLita and the East Village. The suspect first struck at about 6:30 p.m. near Madison Avenue and East 30th Street in Midtown, according to the NYPD. He then approached a 57-year-old Asian woman and punched her once in the face; police said the two did not interact at all before the attack. About 10 minutes later, the same man punched another Asian woman near Fifth Avenue and East 30th Street. The suspect moved to Gramercy Park for his next attack, where he approached a 21-year-old Asian woman and punched her in the face ‚Äî once again, no words were exchanged between the attacker and victim. Five minutes later, near Irving Place and East 17th Street, the man attacked a 25-year-old Asian woman without warning. The next two attacks took place in lower Manhattan, police said. The attacks happened as the Asian-American community in New York City continues to express fear and frustration over recent unprovoked assaults. From Jan. 1 through Feb. 23, which doesn‚Äôt include Sunday‚Äôs attacks, police said there were at least seven anti-Asian hate crime attacks in the city compared to three in the same time period last year. Anyone with information is urged to contact Crime Stoppers at 1-1800-577-8477. Read more at: https://pix11.com/news/local-news/manhattan/suspect-attacked-7-asian-women-in-one-night-nypd/

‚ÄúWhen the Dutch colonised South Africa in the 1650s, Khoisan people like Baartman were "essentially forced into Cape Town" to find work and survive, Natasha Gordon-Chipembere says. In the city, Baartman's body began to gain attention. "She was short, not quite five feet, and she was very curvaceous. She had big hips and a big bum," says Dr Gordon-Chipembere, who is a professor of African diasporic literature and the author of Representation and Black Womanhood: The Legacy of Sarah Baartman. In Cape Town, Baartman worked as a maid at the home of the showman Hendrik Cesars. For some extra cash, Cesars began to show her at the city's hospital, where surgeon Alexander Dunlop was working. He too saw money-making potential in Baartman‚Äù EDUCATION IS ELEVATION!

This school year, the District will hold several Achievement Summits. In partnership with UW-Green Bay, the summits focus on 6th grade students of diverse backgrounds, including Somali, African American, Latino/Latina, Asian American/Pacific Islander and First Nations. Today, our 6th grade Latino students had the opportunity to participate in workshops and tour the campus during their summit. Big thanks to JBS Beef - Green Bay, WI for donating funds to purchase shirts for students and staff with flags that represent where our students are from. The purpose of the Achievement Summits is to provide a positive opportunity for students to see themselves in the world of postsecondary education and learn how to navigate the challenges they may encounter. In addition, the summits focus on creating positive cultural identity, which can improve student success resulting in increased graduation rates and postsecondary enrollment. #GBAPSProud #CollegeReady

Newly released tax filings revealed how Black Lives Matter co-founder Patrisse Cullors used charity funds to pay her friends and family large sums for various 'consulting' services, as well as charter a private flight. The documents reveal that BLM paid a company owned by Damon Turner, the father of Cullors' child, nearly $970,000 to help 'produce live events' and provide other 'creative services.' The co-founder's brother, Paul Cullors, received more than $840,000 for providing security services to the foundation. Leaders have attempted to justify the expense by saying the foundation's protection could not be entrusted to former police professionals who typically run security firms because the BLM movement is known for vehemently protesting law enforcement organizations. A consulting firm run by Shalomyah Bowers, who is BLM's board secretary and has previously served as deputy executive director, was paid more than $2.1 million for providing the organization with operational support, including staffing, fundraising and other key services. The new filing also revealed that Cullors reimbursed BLM $73,523 for a charter flight for foundation-related travel, which the organization says she took in 2021 out of concern for COVID-19 and security threats.
